data.content:
MSTest has a dedicated `CollectionAssert` class plus better assertion methods. Your current approach using `Assert.IsTrue` everywhere gives poor failure messages (just "expected true, got false").

Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Use AreEqual for exact counts — shows expected vs actual on failure
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // CollectionAssert for collection-specific checks
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);

    // Assert.IsTrue is fine for predicate checks, but add a message
    Assert.IsTrue(
        users.All(u => u.IsActive),
        "Expected all users to be active");

    // Use IsNotNull instead of IsTrue for null checks
    var admin = users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin, "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, count)` | Shows expected vs actual values |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` | Clearer intent and message |
| `users.Single(...)` | `users.SingleOrDefault(...)` + `Assert.IsNotNull` | Throws `AssertFailedException` instead of `InvalidOperationException` |

**Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods:**

```csharp
CollectionAssert.Contains(users, expectedUser);
CollectionAssert.DoesNotContain(users, bannedUser);
CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual);       // same order
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual);  // any order
CollectionAssert.IsSubsetOf(subset, superset);
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(users);
```

If you need richer fluent assertions (e.g., `users.Should().OnlyContain(...)`), consider the **FluentAssertions** NuGet package.
